S EC2</li><li>Databases e.g. Google Cloud SQL Service</li><li>Scaling Groups e.g. AWS Auto Scaling Groups</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Each database instance is 1 instance. No matter how many databases you have within the instance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Likewise, each virtual machine that is not part of a scaling group (or managed instance group as Google calls it) is also counted as 1 instance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, we do not count the instances that have been launched by a scaling group.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Please consider this scenario:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You have one Auto Scaling Group in AWS</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This Auto Scaling Group is set to have 5 instances.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the end of each day, this ASG is set to 0 by Cloud Services and instances are terminated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Over a period of a month, you have launched and terminated 150 instances! </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this scenario, will not charge you for 150 instances. Instead, we use this formula:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>We find the maximum number of instances that have ever been launched by the auto-scaling group. In this case, it is 5.</li><li>We will charge you for only five instances and not 150 instances!</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Each instance stop/termination will cost the end-users USD 2.99.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is by far cheaper than any other competitors.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have 5 instances, your metered cost will be:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\",\"fontSize\":\"large\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center has-large-font-size\">2.99 * 5 =  USD 14.95</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This amount is exclusive of tax. The total billed amount will include 10% VAT as well. So your final monthly bill will be:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\",\"fontSize\":\"large\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center has-large-font-size\">USD 16.50 (Sixteen dollars and fifty cents).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Save On Clouds comes with 7 days of free trialling. When your trial period ends we will not remove any of your created groups, users, environments etc. This will enable you to activate your premium membership at any time without having to re-create everything again.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Billing occurs every 30 days after your trial membership ends. For example, if you sign up on the 1st of January, your trial membership will end on 8 of January. Then 30 days after, which is 7th February, we will charged your on-file credit card.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you are billed, you will receive an invoice via your registered email address. Invoices include details of how your usage has been metered.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have any questions regarding the billing, please write to us. Our email address is info@saveonclouds.com.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Pricing', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '27-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-02-19 12:21:42', '2020-02-19 12:21:42', '', 27, 'https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/27-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(31, 1, '2020-02-19 12:21:53', '2020-02-19 12:21:53', '<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":29,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"className\":\"is-style-circle-mask\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image is-style-circle-mask\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/iStock-851244800-1024x878.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-29\"/><figcaption>3d Illustration of Financial documents 3D graphs and pie charts. Pen and Calculator. Top view. Blue theme.</figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When working on the pricing model for Save On Clouds services we had several things in mind:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Simple pricing model</li><li>No hidden costs for the customers</li><li>Affordable cost</li><li>Real savings for the end-users</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is, in fact, one of the areas that we beat our competitors: We work on to bring you real savings and not move the money you save on your cloud costs into our own bank account!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Not only we offer a very simple pricing model but also we try to change our paying customers as low as possible. Especially that we do not charge for how many users and teams you want to have. We do not even charge our clients for the number of cloud accounts e.g. AWS accounts, that they add to the system! </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Basically, we only offer one price tier! And that price is cheap!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once a user signs up, they can create as many users, groups and environments as they wish. They can also add as many cloud accounts as they would like to. We currently support Amazon Web Services, Google Cloud and Microsoft Azure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The system will manage these resources:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Virtual Machines e.g. AWS EC2</li><li>Databases e.g. Google Cloud SQL Service</li><li>Scaling Groups e.g. AWS Auto Scaling Groups</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Each database instance is 1 instance. No matter how many databases you have within the instance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Likewise, each virtual machine that is not part of a scaling group (or managed instance group as Google calls it) is also counted as 1 instance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, we do not count the instances that have been launched by a scaling group.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Please consider this scenario:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You have one Auto Scaling Group in AWS</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This Auto Scaling Group is set to have 5 instances.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the end of each day, this ASG is set to 0 by Cloud Services and instances are terminated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Over a period of a month, you have launched and terminated 150 instances! </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this scenario, will not charge you for 150 instances. Instead, we use this formula:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>We find the maximum number of instances that have ever been launched by the auto-scaling group. In this case, it is 5.</li><li>We will charge you for only five instances and not 150 instances!</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Each instance stop/termination will cost the end-users USD 2.99.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is by far cheaper than any other competitors.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have 5 instances, your metered cost will be:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\",\"fontSize\":\"large\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center has-large-font-size\">2.99 * 5 =  USD 14.95</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This amount is exclusive of tax. The total billed amount will include 10% VAT as well. So your final monthly bill will be:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\",\"fontSize\":\"large\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center has-large-font-size\">USD 16.50 (Sixteen dollars and fifty cents).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Save On Clouds comes with 7 days of free trialling. When your trial period ends we will not remove any of your created groups, users, environments etc. This will enable you to activate your premium membership at any time without having to re-create everything again.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Billing occurs every 30 days after your trial membership ends. For example, if you sign up on the 1st of January, your trial membership will end on 8 of January. Then 30 days after, which is 7th February, we will charged your on-file credit card.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you are billed, you will receive an invoice via your registered email address. Invoices include details of how your usage has been metered.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have any questions regarding the billing, please write to us. Our email address is info@saveonclouds.com.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Pricing', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '27-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-02-19 12:21:53', '2020-02-19 12:21:53', '', 27, 'https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/27-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(32, 1, '2020-02-19 12:23:13', '2020-02-19 12:23:13', '<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":29,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"className\":\"is-style-circle-mask\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image is-style-circle-mask\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/iStock-851244800-1024x878.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-29\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When working on the pricing model for Save On Clouds services we had several things in mind:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Simple pricing model</li><li>No hidden costs for the customers</li><li>Affordable cost</li><li>Real savings for the end-users</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is, in fact, one of the areas that we beat our competitors: We work on to bring you real savings and not move the money you save on your cloud costs into our own bank account!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Not only we offer a very simple pricing model but also we try to change our paying customers as low as possible. Especially that we do not charge for how many users and teams you want to have. We do not even charge our clients for the number of cloud accounts e.g. AWS accounts, that they add to the system! </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Basically, we only offer one price tier! And that price is cheap!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once a user signs up, they can create as many users, groups and environments as they wish. They can also add as many cloud accounts as they would like to. We currently support Amazon Web Services, Google Cloud and Microsoft Azure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The system will manage these resources:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Virtual Machines e.g. AWS EC2</li><li>Databases e.g. Google Cloud SQL Service</li><li>Scaling Groups e.g. AWS Auto Scaling Groups</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Each database instance is 1 instance. No matter how many databases you have within the instance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Likewise, each virtual machine that is not part of a scaling group (or managed instance group as Google calls it) is also counted as 1 instance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>However, we do not count the instances that have been launched by a scaling group.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Please consider this scenario:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You have one Auto Scaling Group in AWS</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This Auto Scaling Group is set to have 5 instances.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the end of each day, this ASG is set to 0 by Cloud Services and instances are terminated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Over a period of a month, you have launched and terminated 150 instances! </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this scenario, will not charge you for 150 instances. Instead, we use this formula:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>We find the maximum number of instances that have ever been launched by the auto-scaling group. In this case, it is 5.</li><li>We will charge you for only five instances and not 150 instances!</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Each instance stop/termination will cost the end-users USD 2.99.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is by far cheaper than any other competitors.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have 5 instances, your metered cost will be:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\",\"fontSize\":\"large\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center has-large-font-size\">2.99 * 5 =  USD 14.95</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This amount is exclusive of tax. The total billed amount will include 10% VAT as well. So your final monthly bill will be:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\",\"fontSize\":\"large\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center has-large-font-size\">USD 16.50 (Sixteen dollars and fifty cents).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Save On Clouds comes with 7 days of free trialling. When your trial period ends we will not remove any of your created groups, users, environments etc. This will enable you to activate your premium membership at any time without having to re-create everything again.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Billing occurs every 30 days after your trial membership ends. For example, if you sign up on the 1st of January, your trial membership will end on 8 of January. Then 30 days after, which is 7th February, we will charged your on-file credit card.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you are billed, you will receive an invoice via your registered email address. Invoices include details of how your usage has been metered.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have any questions regarding the billing, please write to us. Our email address is info@saveonclouds.com.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Pricing', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '27-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-02-19 12:23:13', '2020-02-19 12:23:13', '', 27, 'https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/27-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(33, 1, '2020-02-19 12:59:42', '2020-02-19 12:59:42', '', 'South Lake Union', 'Seattle, USA - Feb 4, 2020: The new Google building entrance in the south lake union with a one way street sign late in the day.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'south-lake-union', '', '', '2020-02-19 12:59:42', '2020-02-19 12:59:42', '', 21, 'http://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/iStock-1204249946.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(34, 1, '2020-02-19 12:59:56', '2020-02-19 12:59:56', '<!-- wp:image {\"id\":33,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/iStock-1204249946-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-33\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Creating a service account in Google and setting up a Google Cloud account in Save On Clouds is a breeze. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To start, log in to the Google Cloud Console via <a href=\"https://console.developers.google.com\">https://console.developers.google.com</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p>You must login to Google Cloud console with a user that has permissions for creating Service Accounts and granting the below roles:</p><p>* Compute Admin</p><p>* SQL Admin</p></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once logged in to the console, expand the drop-down menu which is located on the top-left corner of the console next to Google Cloud API log. Clicking on the down arrow will display the Projects windows.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":22,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/image-10.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-22\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your resources, including the virtual machines and SQL databases reside in a project. If you already have a project you just need to write down its Project Id. Otherwise, click on the \"New Project\" button in the Projects window to create a new project.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":23,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/image-11.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-23\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Creating a new project is as easy and entering a name and optionally choosing an organisational unit.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once the proejct is created and is ready, make sure your newly created project is selected and you are within that project. Then from the left pane, choose the Service Accounts tab</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":24,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/image-12.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-24\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then click on the \"+ Create Service Account\" menu. Your service account must have the below two roles attached to it:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>SQL Admin</li><li>Instance Admin<br></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Click Next until you see the \"Create Key\" button. Click on Create Key button and choose Json for the key type. This will generate a key for your project and downloads it on your computer as a JSON file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Make sure you keep this .The JSON file is safe as it includes information by which others can access your cloud resources.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Head back to Save On Clouds website and login to your account.  Add a Google Cloud account and enter the below:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Name for your account</li><li>Project Id</li><li>Body of the Key JSON file. Open your JSON file in a text editor, copy its content to the clipboard, then paste it in the box provided.</li><li>Click on Save</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Creating a Service Account to Acces Google Cloud', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '21-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-02-19 12:59:56', '2020-02-19 12:59:56', '', 21, 'https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/21-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(35, 1, '2020-04-08 09:01:01', '2020-04-08 09:01:01', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to add a Microsoft Azure account, you will need to collect the below pieces of information:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Subscription Id</li><li>Tenant Id</li><li>Client Id</li><li>Client Secret</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Obviously before you can configure your Azure account to obtain the above data, you will have to make sure that the account you have used to log-in to Azure Portal has sufficient privileges. You will also need an Azure Application.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you do not have an application already, you can register a new application. To do so:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Go to Azure Active Directory</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":40,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-3.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-40\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>On the left-side pane click on App Registration</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":41,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-4.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-41\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Then click on \"New Registration\"</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":42,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-5.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-42\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Click on \"Register\" at the bottom of the screen.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":43,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-6.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-43\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This will create an application for you. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you see the newly created application in the list of applications, click on it and go to its details page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Take notes of Application Id and Directory Id. Application Id is also known as Client Id. Likewise, Directory Id is known as Tenant Id. You will need these two IDs to register your account in Save On Clouds.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The next step is to authorise this application to access the subscription. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In Azure Portal dashboard, find \"Subscriptions\" and click on your desired subscription.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have more than one subscription you will have to register one Cloud Account (in Save On Clouds) per Azure Subscription.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":37,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-37\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":38,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-1.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-38\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Click on the Subscription name (Azure subscription 1 in the above example) and then choose Access Control (IAM) from the list of options.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":39,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-2.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-39\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After clicking on Access Control (IAM), find \"Add role assignment\" card and click on Add button.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":45,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-8.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-45\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>From the Role drop-down box, choose Contributor.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then in the \"Select\" box, type-in the name of your applciation. You only need to type the first few letters of your application.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then click on Save button.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":46,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-9.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-46\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The last step is creating a Secret Key, so that you can make API calls.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To do that, you have to go back to the Azure Portal dashboard, then go to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Azure Active Directory / App Registrations</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Then click on your application, and after seeing the details of your application, click on \"Certificates &amp; Secrets\".</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":47,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-10.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-47\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Click on New Client Secret button.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":48,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-11.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-48\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This will create a new Client Secret. Copy the Client Secret to a safe location and keep it as this is the only time you can see the client secret.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now you have the below information:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Subscription Id (from Home / Subscriptions)</li><li>Tenant Id: It is your Directory Id that you get from Application</li><li>Client Id: It is your Application Id that you get from Application</li><li>Client Secret</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By having the four above keys, head back to Save On Cloud and:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Go to Cloud Accounts</li><li>Click on Azure Icon</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":49,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-12.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-49\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Enter Subscription Id, Tenant Id, Client Id and Client Secret</li><li>Enter a name for the connection</li><li>Click on Test Connection</li><li>Click on \"Create Account\" button.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Please be advised that if you have multiple Resource Groups, you<strong> do not</strong> need to register each resource group separately. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Adding an Azure Account', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'adding-an-azure-account', '', '', '2020-04-12 00:54:40', '2020-04-12 00:54:40', '', 0, 'http://saveoncloudsblog.cloud/?p=35', 0, 'post', '', 0),
