(97, 1, '2020-04-13 00:24:49', '2020-04-13 00:24:49', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using Schedules you can stop and start your Cloud Resources at specific times.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After creating a Schedule you can attach it to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>A single Cloud Resource such as a virtual machine (e.g. AWS EC2)</li><li>An Environment</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We recommend that you create Environments and then attach the schedules to the environments, rather than attaching them to single resources. This will reduce your administration and configuration overhead.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Creating and Editing Schedules</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To create a Schedule, click on the Schedules item in the main menu.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":90,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://info.saveonclouds.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-28.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-90\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This will take you to the Schedule\'s listing page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":91,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://info.saveonclouds.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-29.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-91\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To create a new Schedule, click on \"+ Create New\" button.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":95,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://info.saveonclouds.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-33.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-95\"/><figcaption>Creating a new Schedule</figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Clicking on the \"Create New\" button will open the Create Schedule dialog box. In this modal window you can enter the below information:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Name: A short name for the schedule. This appears on the Cloud Resources and Environments pages.</li><li>Description: Provider a description for the Schedule</li><li>Enabled: By default Schedules are enabled. You can temporarily disable a schedule by un-checking the Enabled option.</li><li>Schedule is created for: Save On Clouds allows users to manage their own cloud resources as well as the cloud resources of the other accounts, when some other accounts invites the user to do so. When creating a Schedule you must specify whether this Schedule will be used in conjuration with your own Cloud Resources and Environments, or with the resources of another account.  By default \"Schedule is created for\" option is set you the currently logged-in user.</li><li>Time Zone:  The days and times that you specify in the scheduling panel (calendar) are based on the time zone that is seen in the Time Zone drop-down list. The Time Zone drop-down list is, by default, set to the current user\'s profile time zone. If, when you open the New Schedule window, the time zone is not set correctly, please go to the Profile page and update your default time zone.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Defining the scheduling pattern</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When defining the scheduling pattern, which means on which days and times your resources must be ON, you can choose one of the below three frequencies (or ac curacies):</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Hourly (default). </li><li>30 Minutes</li><li>15 Minutes</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you change the frequency, the size of the boxes in the calendar will change, however your current selection will be retained.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the calendar:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Green color means that resources will be ON</li><li>Blank or White means that resources will be OFF</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":96,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://info.saveonclouds.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/schedules.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-96\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Click on Save button to save your schedules.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At any time, by clicking on the Edit button in the Schedules listing page you can get back to this window and change your schedules.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once a schedule is created you can go to either \"Cloud Resources\" or \"Environments\" and attach the schedule to your desired entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p>When a Cloud Resource such as a Virtual Machine has a Schedule attached to it, that Schedule will be preferred to the Schedules that are attached to Environments. If you want to control the up time of your resources by the use of Environments, do not attach a Schedule to a Cloud Resource directly.</p></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Schedules', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '89-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-04-13 00:24:49', '2020-04-13 00:24:49', '', 89, 'https://info.saveonclouds.com/89-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(98, 1, '2020-04-13 00:27:59', '2020-04-13 00:27:59', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using Schedules you can stop and start your Cloud Resources at specific times.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After creating a Schedule you can attach it to:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>A single Cloud Resource such as a virtual machine (e.g. AWS EC2)</li><li>An Environment</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We recommend that you create Environments and then attach the schedules to the environments, rather than attaching them to single resources. This will reduce your administration and configuration overhead.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Creating and Editing Schedules</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To create a Schedule, click on the Schedules item in the main menu.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":90,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://info.saveonclouds.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-28.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-90\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This will take you to the Schedule\'s listing page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":91,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://info.saveonclouds.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-29.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-91\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To create a new Schedule, click on \"+ Create New\" button.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":95,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://info.saveonclouds.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-33.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-95\"/><figcaption>Creating a new Schedule</figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Clicking on the \"Create New\" button will open the Create Schedule dialog box. In this modal window you can enter the below information:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Name: A short name for the schedule. This appears on the Cloud Resources and Environments pages.</li><li>Description: Provider a description for the Schedule</li><li>Enabled: By default Schedules are enabled. You can temporarily disable a schedule by un-checking the Enabled option.</li><li>Schedule is created for: Save On Clouds allows users to manage their own cloud resources as well as the cloud resources of the other accounts, when some other accounts invites the user to do so. When creating a Schedule you must specify whether this Schedule will be used in conjuration with your own Cloud Resources and Environments, or with the resources of another account.  By default \"Schedule is created for\" option is set you the currently logged-in user.</li><li>Time Zone:  The days and times that you specify in the scheduling panel (calendar) are based on the time zone that is seen in the Time Zone drop-down list. The Time Zone drop-down list is, by default, set to the current user\'s profile time zone. If, when you open the New Schedule window, the time zone is not set correctly, please go to the Profile page and update your default time zone.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Defining the scheduling pattern</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When defining the scheduling pattern, which means on which days and times your resources must be ON, you can choose one of the below three frequencies (or ac curacies):</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Hourly (default). </li><li>30 Minutes</li><li>15 Minutes</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you change the frequency, the size of the boxes in the calendar will change, however your current selection will be retained.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the calendar:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Green color means that resources will be ON</li><li>Blank or White means that resources will be OFF</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":96,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://info.saveonclouds.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/schedules.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-96\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Click on Save button to save your schedules.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At any time, by clicking on the Edit button in the Schedules listing page you can get back to this window and change your schedules.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once a schedule is created you can go to either \"Cloud Resources\" or \"Environments\" and attach the schedule to your desired entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p>When a Cloud Resource such as a Virtual Machine has a Schedule attached to it, that Schedule will be preferred to the Schedules that are attached to Environments. If you want to control the up time of your resources by the use of Environments, do not attach a Schedule to a Cloud Resource directly.</p></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Schedules', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '89-autosave-v1', '', '', '2020-04-13 00:27:59', '2020-04-13 00:27:59', '', 89, 'https://info.saveonclouds.com/89-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(99, 1, '2020-04-13 01:20:35', '2020-04-13 01:20:35', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Environments are an effective way of grouping your resources and optimising their utilisation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p>An Environment is essentially a Query. It is not the actual list of resources. Which means the resources that fit in a given Environment can change in the future.</p></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To define a query, click on the \"Environments\" item in the main menu (right side of the screen).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":100,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://info.saveonclouds.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-34.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-100\"/><figcaption>Environments item in the main menu</figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This will take you to the Environment\'s listing page. To create a new Environment, click on \"+ Create New\" button.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":101,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://info.saveonclouds.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-35.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-101\"/><figcaption>The Create New button</figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Clicking on the Create New button will open the Edit Environment screen.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":102,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://info.saveonclouds.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-36.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-102\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this screen:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Provide a name for the Environment. For example: Staging</li><li>Choose the Owner. This is useful when you have been invited to manage the environments of some other accounts too.</li><li>Schedule: Choose the Schedule that you want to associate with this Environment.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Defining the Environment\'s query</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As said before, each Environment is a \"Definition\" or a \"Query\" by which the Cloud Resources are discovered. This means that you do not actually include the resources in Environments, but rather you tell the Environment that how the resources must be discovered.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Please bear in mind that if in the future you add new Cloud Resources e.g. Virtual Machines that match an Environment\'s query, they will be picked up and processed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To add a new rule, simple click on the green \"Add Rule\" button. Each rule can have a key, a criteria and a value.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A key can be one of the below:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Resource Name: The unique identifier of the resource. For example i-xxxx is the format of the resource name of AWS EC2 instances.</li><li>Cloud Type: The provider type which can be AWS, Azure or GCP.</li><li>At Least One Tag Key: If your resources have Tags or Labels, at least of of those tags/labels.</li><li>At Least One Tag Value: If your resources have Tags or Labels, at least the value of one of those tags/labels</li><li>At Least One Tag Key/Value: If your resources have Tags or Labels, at least of tag and value must match.</li><li>Cloud Account: One of the accounts that you have registered in Cloud Accounts page.</li><li>State: The state of the resource. Can be Stop or Running.</li><li>Location: The region or zone of the resource depending on the cloud provider. The Location value can be seen in the Cloud Resources page.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The middle drop-down list includes the Cirteria. Criteria may change based on the Key. For example if the value of a Key is a text, e.g. the value of a Location, then you will have the below options:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>equals</li><li>not equal</li><li>begins with</li><li>doesn\'t begin with</li><li>contains</li><li>doesn\'t contain</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whilst if the value is a list of options the criteria can be:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>equals</li><li>doesn\'t equal</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To add a new Rule, again click on the Add Rule button. By default when you add a new Rule, the condition is AND. If you want to put OR between two conditions, click on the \"OR\" button.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":103,\"width\":610,\"height\":108,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://info.saveonclouds.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-37.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-103\" width=\"610\" height=\"108\"/><figcaption>Use AND or OR buttons to combine the rules</figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Not only you can combine individual rules but also can you create groups of rules and combine them together!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To add a Group, simply click on the \"Add group\" button (which is next to \"Add rule\" button).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The \"AND\" and \"OR\" options apply on the Groups too so that you can combine groups as well.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":104,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://info.saveonclouds.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-38.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-104\"/><figcaption>Combining rules and groups</figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the end, click on Test to see a preview of the resources that may get included in the Environment. If everything looks good, click on the Save button to save the Environment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p>Please be advised that when you associate a Schedule with an Environment, the Schedule will not affect the Cloud Resources that:</p><p>1- Are included in the Environment</p><p>2- They have a Schedule directly associated to them</p></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Schedules that are directly attached to a Cloud Resource always take priority over the Schedule that is attached to an Environment. Also, if you attach the system Schedule of \"Do Not Disturb\" to a cloud resources, they will not be affected by the Schedule that is associated with the Environment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>STOP and START environments</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you do not associate a Schedule to an Environment, then a STOP and a START button will appear next to the Environment in the listing page.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":105,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"https://info.saveonclouds.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/image-39-1024x95.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-105\"/><figcaption>Stop and Start buttons</figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you click on the Start button, all the Stopped resources in that Environment will be Started (they will receive a Start command).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you click on the Stop button, all the Running resources in that Environment will be Stopped (they will receive a Stop command).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To know when an Environment is stopped or started, create a Notification Channel (via Notifications) menu and subscribe to the Environment\'s events.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://info.saveonclouds.com/schedules/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Read more about Schedules.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Environments', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'environments', '', '', '2020-04-13 01:20:35', '2020-04-13 01:20:35', '', 0, 'http://info.saveonclouds.com/?p=99', 0, 'post', '', 0),
