d on knowing your current use and predicting future use. In other words, try to develop tools to make your cloud existence easier, and that includes tools to optimize costs - to optimize your cloud usage!&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 5, 7</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You will definitely not need every AWS service, but you should look for services that reduce operational overhead wherever possible. Route 53, RDS, EKS and ECS are just some of the AWS services you can use to reduce operating costs in the cloud. As always, you should look at the available economic resources of AWS - whitepapers such as the introduction to the cloud economy explain the economics of lowering operating costs and the advantages and disadvantages of each.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"textColor\":\"secondary\",\"backgroundColor\":\"subtle-background\",\"fontSize\":\"normal\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-color has-background has-normal-font-size has-secondary-color has-subtle-background-background-color\">SAVE ON CLOUDS can help you reduce your spend on AWS EC2, AWS RDS for MySQL and SQL Server, as well as AWS RDS Aurora Clusters.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\",\"textColor\":\"accent\",\"backgroundColor\":\"subtle-background\",\"fontSize\":\"large\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-color has-background has-text-align-center has-large-font-size has-accent-color has-subtle-background-background-color\"><a href=\"https://saveonclouds.com\">Visit Save On Clouds Now and Start Your Saving</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Cited Sources</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.srijan.net/blog/aws-cost-optimization\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://www.srijan.net/blog/aws-cost-optimization</a>&nbsp;<sup>0</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://dzone.com/articles/7-aws-cost-optimization-techniques\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://dzone.com/articles/7-aws-cost-optimization-techniques</a>&nbsp;<sup>1</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.cloudhealthtech.com/blog/10-aws-cost-optimization-best-practices\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://www.cloudhealthtech.com/blog/10-aws-cost-optimization-best-practices</a>&nbsp;<sup>2</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.botmetric.com/blog/top-5-aws-cost-saving-and-optimization-strategies/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://www.botmetric.com/blog/top-5-aws-cost-saving-and-optimization-strategies/</a>&nbsp;<sup>3</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://devops.com/why-aws-cost-optimization-is-about-more-than-saving-money/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://devops.com/why-aws-cost-optimization-is-about-more-than-saving-money/</a>&nbsp;<sup>4</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.apptio.com/emerge/aws-reserved-instances-cost-optimization/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://www.apptio.com/emerge/aws-reserved-instances-cost-optimization/</a>&nbsp;<sup>5</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://wa.aws.amazon.com/wat.pillar.costOptimization.en.html\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://wa.aws.amazon.com/wat.pillar.costOptimization.en.html</a>&nbsp;<sup>6</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://newrelic.com/solutions/aws/aws-cost-optimization/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://newrelic.com/solutions/aws/aws-cost-optimization/</a>&nbsp;<sup>7</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://cloud.netapp.com/blog/cost-optimization-concepts-tools-and-best-practices-aws-cvo-blg\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://cloud.netapp.com/blog/cost-optimization-concepts-tools-and-best-practices-aws-cvo-blg</a>&nbsp;<sup>8</sup></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'AWS Cost Optimization', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '145-autosave-v1', '', '', '2020-05-23 07:59:33', '2020-05-23 07:59:33', '', 145, 'https://info.saveonclouds.com/145-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(151, 1, '2020-05-23 08:00:30', '2020-05-23 08:00:30', '<!-- wp:image {\"id\":146,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"className\":\"is-style-default\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-style-default\"><img src=\"https://info.saveonclouds.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/iStock-1165055244.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-146\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cost optimization is a pillar of AWS\'s well-structured framework, and our vision is to leverage machine learning to help you navigate the cloud, especially in terms of capacity and cost. Due to the lack of consulting talent, complexity analysis tools to optimize costs exist only for top companies that spend more than $10,000 per month, which is greatly neglected. Amazon knows that if you use your resources well, you are likely to use more AWS.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 1</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But with the advent of deep learning and AI, we believe you can find cost savings in your AWS account and help you use more. To better understand cost optimization, here are a few quick best practices that can help significantly reduce your Amazon AWS bill. Identification of EC2 instances that are not at full capacity, downgrading of the instance size and shifting the instance size to another instance family in order to save costs.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 1, 8</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After selecting an Optimized Storage instance, switch to an all-purpose instance to see if your application is not as memory intensive as expected. For example, you could use S3 Standard for storage, while S 3 Glacier would suit your needs.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 4, 8</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you have identified such a problem, you can take steps to spend less money to maintain the same level of performance across all your cloud workloads.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 4</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A basic best practice is to use tools like AWS Trusted Advisor to ensure that you set up your infrastructure cost-effectively from the outset. Tools such as AWS\'s Tr trusted Advisor and Botmetric can provide insight into unused resources so you can clean them up to save costs. Bot Metric also offers automation jobs to make sure you keep track of your cloud cost optimization for unused resources and one to remove them.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 3, 4</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you introduce a large number of resources into your AWS cloud infrastructure every day, it is inevitable that resources will go unused or unused.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 3</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of the best ways to cut costs is to reserve EC2, RDS and Redshift to reduce costs from 20% to 60%.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 3</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this post, we will review Amazon\'s cost optimization strategy and show how NetApp Cloud Volumes and ONTAP can help you significantly reduce your cloud service bill. Get a grip on your AWS costs with free Amazon tools that help you manage costs and best practices to reduce Amazon\'s warehousing costs. Before you start optimizing your costs on Amazon, it is important to understand the tools Amazon gives you to optimize and save costs, such as the AWS Cost Optimization Toolkit.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 8</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this table, we briefly explain some of the principles to watch out for, such as Spot Instances, NetApp Cloud Volumes and ONTAP. Where your system can tolerate the use of fleet servers (where individual servers can come and go dynamically) or the use of HPC and big data, spot instances are appropriate.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 6, 8</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Adequate service selection can also reduce usage costs, such as CloudFront, which minimizes data transmission and eliminates costs by using Amazon Aurora to eliminate costly database licensing costs. By including these costs in your service selection, you can adjust your deployment and monitor usage using tools such as AWS Trusted Advisor to regularly review and help you with AWS usage.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 0, 6</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Amazon CloudWatch is also an important AWS service that supports an appropriately deployed approach that allows you to collect and track metrics about your usage. The AWS Management Console can modify the attributes of your AWS services and help adapt resources to your needs and changing requirements.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 0</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The most common solution to reporting problems is to reserve reserved instances that are purchased for predictable workloads. AWS offers a number of reservation options for AWS services such as AWS CloudWatch, AWS Backup and Replication, and AWS Red Hat Enterprise Services.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 0, 2</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let us start with the proper timetable for reserved instances, which I have already mentioned but would like to mention. Cost optimization is an important component of a well - an architectural framework that is often overlooked, and for good reason. You can save a fraction of the cost you claim, although you can save a lot more.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 2, 5</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Reserved instances are a great way to optimize your AWS costs while saving up to 70% of your on-demand rate. By optimizing costs, you build a more efficient cloud that helps you focus your cloud spending where you need it most, freeing up resources to invest in developing competitive differentiators.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 5</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Making use of these savings involves a multi-point strategy based on knowing your current use and predicting future use. In other words, try to develop tools to make your cloud existence easier, and that includes tools to optimize costs - to optimize your cloud usage!&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 5, 7</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You will definitely not need every AWS service, but you should look for services that reduce operational overhead wherever possible. Route 53, RDS, EKS and ECS are just some of the AWS services you can use to reduce operating costs in the cloud. As always, you should look at the available economic resources of AWS - whitepapers such as the introduction to the cloud economy explain the economics of lowering operating costs and the advantages and disadvantages of each.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"textColor\":\"secondary\",\"backgroundColor\":\"subtle-background\",\"fontSize\":\"normal\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-color has-background has-normal-font-size has-secondary-color has-subtle-background-background-color\">SAVE ON CLOUDS can help you reduce your spend on AWS EC2, AWS RDS for MySQL and SQL Server, as well as AWS RDS Aurora Clusters.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\",\"textColor\":\"accent\",\"backgroundColor\":\"subtle-background\",\"fontSize\":\"large\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-color has-background has-text-align-center has-large-font-size has-accent-color has-subtle-background-background-color\"><a href=\"https://saveonclouds.com\">Visit Save On Clouds Now and Start Your Saving</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Cited Sources</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.srijan.net/blog/aws-cost-optimization\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://www.srijan.net/blog/aws-cost-optimization</a>&nbsp;<sup>0</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://dzone.com/articles/7-aws-cost-optimization-techniques\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://dzone.com/articles/7-aws-cost-optimization-techniques</a>&nbsp;<sup>1</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.cloudhealthtech.com/blog/10-aws-cost-optimization-best-practices\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://www.cloudhealthtech.com/blog/10-aws-cost-optimization-best-practices</a>&nbsp;<sup>2</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.botmetric.com/blog/top-5-aws-cost-saving-and-optimization-strategies/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://www.botmetric.com/blog/top-5-aws-cost-saving-and-optimization-strategies/</a>&nbsp;<sup>3</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://devops.com/why-aws-cost-optimization-is-about-more-than-saving-money/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://devops.com/why-aws-cost-optimization-is-about-more-than-saving-money/</a>&nbsp;<sup>4</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.apptio.com/emerge/aws-reserved-instances-cost-optimization/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://www.apptio.com/emerge/aws-reserved-instances-cost-optimization/</a>&nbsp;<sup>5</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://wa.aws.amazon.com/wat.pillar.costOptimization.en.html\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://wa.aws.amazon.com/wat.pillar.costOptimization.en.html</a>&nbsp;<sup>6</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://newrelic.com/solutions/aws/aws-cost-optimization/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://newrelic.com/solutions/aws/aws-cost-optimization/</a>&nbsp;<sup>7</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://cloud.netapp.com/blog/cost-optimization-concepts-tools-and-best-practices-aws-cvo-blg\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://cloud.netapp.com/blog/cost-optimization-concepts-tools-and-best-practices-aws-cvo-blg</a>&nbsp;<sup>8</sup></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'AWS Cost Optimization', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '145-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-05-23 08:00:30', '2020-05-23 08:00:30', '', 145, 'https://info.saveonclouds.com/145-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(152, 1, '2020-05-31 01:06:21', '2020-05-31 01:06:21', '<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"className\":\"is-style-rounded\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image is-style-rounded\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://i0.wp.com/www.infrakloud.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/Azure-Container-Service_COLOR.png?fit=512%2C512&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"Windows Server Container on an AKS (Azure Kubernetes Service ...\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Microsoft Azure has introduced a Container Services Calculator to calculate the estimated cost of resource consumption and consumption. AKS is a free container service where you do not have to pay anything for the cluster management of Kubernetes. You must pay to ensure that the resources you consume are used cost-effectively and efficiently, and not at the expense of other services. <sup>Sources: 5</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AKS is also a reliable resource that brings Kubernetes and DevOps together to secure your devOps implementation of Kubersets. You need to create a free account, build and deploy a KubertnetES cluster, manage and manage your Kubermanes environment, and then use AKS to create, deploy, configure, monitor, test, debug, scale, maintain, or deploy your Kuber netbooks.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 5</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you use Azure Container Instance (ACI) ) AKS, you can also apply it to your Kubernetes virtual nodes. In this way, we can use the virtual node AKs to provide a pod by starting it with an Azure container instance (ACI) that starts in a few seconds and enables AKS to run with the required resources.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 5</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Unlike other managed Kubernetes providers, Azure does not charge you for using the AKS service, and you only pay the usual IaaS costs for the resources running in your AKS cluster. Most of the cost of an AKs cluster are the VMs in which the containers run, but you can also scale additional pods by running a Kubersetes cluster or managing additional servers in a KuberNetes environment.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 0, 5</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Microsoft provides AKS Azure Kubernetes services that allow you to run a fully managed Kubersetes cluster on Azure without the pain of a control plan. You don\'t pay for the master node in AKs, and if you can reduce the cost of worker nods, you could save a considerable amount of money on a cluster that doesn\'t need to be operational around the clock.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 0, 1</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We decided to leave WebSite on the Azure App Service Plan and use an instance based on its CPU / RAM load balancing. So we became aware of the service of AKS Azure Kubernetes and its costs and decided against it.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 1</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As we all now know, Kubernetes is an open - source, cross - platform, cl - tagged ceph - kubernete - rook - ak that runs on a top-level cloud infrastructure like Azure. The orchestration platform for this provides the perfect cloud - native environment in which MinIO can be deployed and scaled. AzureKuber (AKS) Provides a managed KubersnetES service that reduces deployment and core management tasks, including deployment, scaling, monitoring and coordination of upgrades.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 2</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you want an S3 replacement that you would run in the cloud, you can use Rook to configure a Kubernetes cluster and start storing objects on the same API that you would use to store objects in S 3.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 2</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This one-week accelerated online class equips students to containers workloads in docker containers and deploy them in a Kubernetes cluster, as provided by Google\'s Kubersetes. Crossplane is an open source add-on to Kubertools that is supported by the cloud - native community. This volume is called an agent that acts in the KuBERNETES cluster and stores objects in a pod. The volume embeds the same API as the pods into the container as well as all Kuber netbooks, using Kubeletes abstraction to manage the pod memory and supporting nodes that host PODs running on it.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 4</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the end, with the help of Crossplane and the Kubeletes API, the reader will be able to develop and deploy an application in just a few hours that takes full advantage of the Kubernetes platform.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 4</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS) brings these solutions together so that customers can quickly and easily create a fully managed container orchestration service in the Azure Public Cloud. AKs is the first fully managed, open, open source, cloud native and open source container orchestrator service available on Microsoft\'s Public Clouds since June 2018, and can be used to deploy and manage Docker containers and container-based applications in a cluster environment and within cluster environments. Surely it is a great opportunity for developers to develop their modern applications that use Kubersetes in an Azure architecture where Azure container instances are the most common way to use containers in publicity clouds.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 5</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS) competes with other open source container orchestration services such as Docker Swarm, Docker Containers and Docker Hub. Azure Container instances help developers reduce the cost of deploying and operating their applications in a Kubersetes architecture, as well as deploying and managing containers in the cloud.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 3, 5</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AKS has several features that are attractive to users of Microsoft Azure, and it only charges for calculating usage. AKS offers the ability to easily create, maintain and monitor its clusters and control them from the cloud. We have created a test cluster to examine some of the features offered by AK SysOps and the Azure Kubernetes service.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Sources</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://blog.headforcloud.com/2018/07/17/save-money-on-aks/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://blog.headforcloud.com/2018/07/17/save-money-on-aks/</a>&nbsp;<sup>0</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://blog.dirk-eisenberg.de/2018/07/17/kubernetes-vs-azure-app-services-webjobs-why-i-switched/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://blog.dirk-eisenberg.de/2018/07/17/kubernetes-vs-azure-app-services-webjobs-why-i-switched/</a>&nbsp;<sup>1</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://bookmybooks.co.in/nrwl5db/kubernetes-rook-vs.html\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">http://bookmybooks.co.in/nrwl5db/kubernetes-rook-vs.html</a>&nbsp;<sup>2</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.bluematador.com/blog/creating-a-kubernetes-cluster-in-azure-kubernetes-service\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://www.bluematador.com/blog/creating-a-kubernetes-cluster-in-azure-kubernetes-service</a>&nbsp;<sup>3</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://accemauritanie.com/vynypbq/kubernetes-in-action.html\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">http://accemauritanie.com/vynypbq/kubernetes-in-action.html</a>&nbsp;<sup>4</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://cloudacademy.com/blog/azure-kubernetes-service-aks-what-is-it-and-why-do-we-use-it/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://cloudacademy.com/blog/azure-kubernetes-service-aks-what-is-it-and-why-do-we-use-it/</a>&nbsp;<sup>5</sup></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->', 'Azure Aks Cost Opitmization', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'azure-aks-cost-opitmization', '', '', '2020-05-31 01:14:33', '2020-05-31 01:14:33', '', 0, 'http://info.saveonclouds.com/?p=152', 0, 'post', '', 0);
