(153, 1, '2020-05-31 01:05:41', '2020-05-31 01:05:41', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Microsoft Azure has introduced a Container Services Calculator to calculate the estimated cost of resource consumption and consumption. AKS is a free container service where you do not have to pay anything for the cluster management of Kubernetes. You must pay to ensure that the resources you consume are used cost-effectively and efficiently, and not at the expense of other services.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 5</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AKS is also a reliable resource that brings Kubernetes and DevOps together to secure your devOps implementation of Kubersets. You need to create a free account, build and deploy a KubertnetES cluster, manage and manage your Kubermanes environment, and then use AKS to create, deploy, configure, monitor, test, debug, scale, maintain, or deploy your Kuber netbooks.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 5</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you use Azure Container Instance (ACI) ) AKS, you can also apply it to your Kubernetes virtual nodes. In this way, we can use the virtual node AKs to provide a pod by starting it with an Azure container instance (ACI) that starts in a few seconds and enables AKS to run with the required resources.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 5</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Unlike other managed Kubernetes providers, Azure does not charge you for using the AKS service, and you only pay the usual IaaS costs for the resources running in your AKS cluster. Most of the cost of an AKs cluster are the VMs in which the containers run, but you can also scale additional pods by running a Kubersetes cluster or managing additional servers in a KuberNetes environment.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 0, 5</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Microsoft provides AKS Azure Kubernetes services that allow you to run a fully managed Kubersetes cluster on Azure without the pain of a control plan. You don\'t pay for the master node in AKs, and if you can reduce the cost of worker nods, you could save a considerable amount of money on a cluster that doesn\'t need to be operational around the clock.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 0, 1</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We decided to leave WebSite on the Azure App Service Plan and use an instance based on its CPU / RAM load balancing. So we became aware of the service of AKS Azure Kubernetes and its costs and decided against it.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 1</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As we all now know, Kubernetes is an open - source, cross - platform, cl - tagged ceph - kubernete - rook - ak that runs on a top-level cloud infrastructure like Azure. The orchestration platform for this provides the perfect cloud - native environment in which MinIO can be deployed and scaled. AzureKuber (AKS) Provides a managed KubersnetES service that reduces deployment and core management tasks, including deployment, scaling, monitoring and coordination of upgrades.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 2</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you want an S3 replacement that you would run in the cloud, you can use Rook to configure a Kubernetes cluster and start storing objects on the same API that you would use to store objects in S 3.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 2</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This one-week accelerated online class equips students to containers workloads in docker containers and deploy them in a Kubernetes cluster, as provided by Google\'s Kubersetes. Crossplane is an open source add-on to Kubertools that is supported by the cloud - native community. This volume is called an agent that acts in the KuBERNETES cluster and stores objects in a pod. The volume embeds the same API as the pods into the container as well as all Kuber netbooks, using Kubeletes abstraction to manage the pod memory and supporting nodes that host PODs running on it.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 4</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the end, with the help of Crossplane and the Kubeletes API, the reader will be able to develop and deploy an application in just a few hours that takes full advantage of the Kubernetes platform.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 4</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS) brings these solutions together so that customers can quickly and easily create a fully managed container orchestration service in the Azure Public Cloud. AKs is the first fully managed, open, open source, cloud native and open source container orchestrator service available on Microsoft\'s Public Clouds since June 2018, and can be used to deploy and manage Docker containers and container-based applications in a cluster environment and within cluster environments. Surely it is a great opportunity for developers to develop their modern applications that use Kubersetes in an Azure architecture where Azure container instances are the most common way to use containers in publicity clouds.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 5</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS) competes with other open source container orchestration services such as Docker Swarm, Docker Containers and Docker Hub. Azure Container instances help developers reduce the cost of deploying and operating their applications in a Kubersetes architecture, as well as deploying and managing containers in the cloud.&nbsp;<sup>Sources: 3, 5</sup></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AKS has several features that are attractive to users of Microsoft Azure, and it only charges for calculating usage. AKS offers the ability to easily create, maintain and monitor its clusters and control them from the cloud. We have created a test cluster to examine some of the features offered by AK SysOps and the Azure Kubernetes service.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Sources</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://blog.headforcloud.com/2018/07/17/save-money-on-aks/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://blog.headforcloud.com/2018/07/17/save-money-on-aks/</a>&nbsp;<sup>0</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://blog.dirk-eisenberg.de/2018/07/17/kubernetes-vs-azure-app-services-webjobs-why-i-switched/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://blog.dirk-eisenberg.de/2018/07/17/kubernetes-vs-azure-app-services-webjobs-why-i-switched/</a>&nbsp;<sup>1</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://bookmybooks.co.in/nrwl5db/kubernetes-rook-vs.html\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">http://bookmybooks.co.in/nrwl5db/kubernetes-rook-vs.html</a>&nbsp;<sup>2</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.bluematador.com/blog/creating-a-kubernetes-cluster-in-azure-kubernetes-service\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://www.bluematador.com/blog/creating-a-kubernetes-cluster-in-azure-kubernetes-service</a>&nbsp;<sup>3</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://accemauritanie.com/vynypbq/kubernetes-in-action.html\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">http://accemauritanie.com/vynypbq/kubernetes-in-action.html</a>&nbsp;<sup>4</sup></li><li><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://cloudacademy.com/blog/azure-kubernetes-service-aks-what-is-it-and-why-do-we-use-it/\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">https://cloudacademy.com/blog/azure-kubernetes-service-aks-what-is-it-and-why-do-we-use-it/</a>&nbsp;<sup>5</sup></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->', 'Azure Aks Cost Opitmization', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '152-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-05-31 01:05:41', '2020-05-31 01:05:41', '', 152, 'https://info.saveonclouds.com/152-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
